# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: projective-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In geometry, the **cross-ratio**, also called the **double ratio** and **anharmonic ratio**, is a number associated with a list of four collinear points, particularly points on a projective line.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] where an orientation of the line determines the sign of each distance and the distance is measured as projected into Euclidean space.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] (If one of the four points is the line's point at infinity, then the two distances involving that point are dropped from the formula.) The point D is the harmonic conjugate of C with respect to A and B precisely if the cross-ratio of the quadruple is −1, called the *harmonic ratio*.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio can therefore be regarded as measuring the quadruple's deviation from this ratio; hence the name *anharmonic ratio*.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio is preserved by linear fractional transformations.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] It is essentially the only projective invariant of a quadruple of collinear points; this underlies its importance for projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio had been defined in deep antiquity, possibly already by Euclid, and was considered by Pappus, who noted its key invariance property.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] It was extensively studied in the 19th century.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Variants of this concept exist for a quadruple of concurrent lines on the projective plane and a quadruple of points on the Riemann sphere.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In the Cayley–Klein model of hyperbolic geometry, the distance between points is expressed in terms of a certain cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Pappus of Alexandria made implicit use of concepts equivalent to the cross-ratio in his *Collection: Book VII*.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Early users of Pappus included Isaac Newton, Michel Chasles, and Robert Simson.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In 1986 Alexander Jones made a translation of the original by Pappus, then wrote a commentary on how the lemmas of Pappus relate to modern terminology.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Modern use of the cross ratio in projective geometry began with Lazare Carnot in 1803 with his book *Géométrie de Position*.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Chasles coined the French term *rapport anharmonique* [anharmonic ratio] in 1837.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] German geometers call it *das Doppelverhältnis* [double ratio].
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Carl von Staudt was unsatisfied with past definitions of the cross-ratio relying on algebraic manipulation of Euclidean distances rather than being based purely on synthetic projective geometry concepts.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] His *algebra of throws* provides an approach to numerical propositions, usually taken as axioms, but proven in projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The English term "cross-ratio" was introduced in 1878 by William Kingdon Clifford.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] with the notation $WX:YZ$ defined to mean the signed ratio of the displacement from W to X to the displacement from Y to Z.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] For collinear displacements this is a dimensionless quantity.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross ratio can for example be defined for pencils of lines, circles, or conics.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] where ${\textstyle AC:CB}$ describes the ratio with which the point C divides the line segment AB, and ${\textstyle AD:DB}$ describes the ratio with which the point D divides that same line segment.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross ratio then appears as a ratio of ratios, describing how the two points C and D are situated with respect to the line segment AB.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] As long as the points A, B, C, and D are distinct, the cross ratio (*A*, *B*; *C*, *D*) will be a non-zero real number.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Four points can be ordered in 4! = 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 24 ways, but there are only six ways for partitioning them into two unordered pairs.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio is a **projective invariant** in the sense that it is preserved by the projective transformations of a projective line.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In particular, if four points lie on a straight line ${\textstyle L}$ in ${\textstyle {\mathbf {R}}^{2}}$ then their cross-ratio is a well-defined quantity, because any choice of the origin and even of the scale on the line will yield the same value of the cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Furthermore, let ${\textstyle \{L_{i}\mid 1\leq i\leq 4\}}$ be four distinct lines in the plane passing through the same point ${\textstyle Q}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Then any line ${\textstyle L}$ not passing through ${\textstyle Q}$ intersects these lines in four distinct points ${\textstyle P_{i}}$ (if ${\textstyle L}$ is parallel to ${\textstyle L_{i}}$ then the corresponding intersection point is "at infinity").
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Therefore, the invariance of the cross-ratio under projective automorphisms of the line implies (in fact, is equivalent to) the independence of the cross-ratio of the four collinear points ${\textstyle \{P_{i}\}}$ on the lines ${\textstyle \{L_{i}\}}$ from the choice of the line that contains them.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] If four collinear points are represented in homogeneous coordinates by vectors $\alpha ,\beta ,\gamma ,\delta$ such that $\gamma =a\alpha +b\beta$ and $\delta =c\alpha +d\beta$ , then their cross-ratio is $(b/a)/(d/c)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Arthur Cayley and Felix Klein found an application of the cross-ratio to non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Given a nonsingular conic C in the real projective plane, its stabilizer $G_{C}$ in the projective group $G=\operatorname {PGL} (3,\mathbb {R} )$ acts transitively on the points in the interior of C .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] However, there is an invariant for the action of $G_{C}$ on *pairs* of points.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In fact, every such invariant is expressible as a function of the appropriate cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Explicitly, let the conic be the unit circle.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] For any two points P and Q, inside the unit circle .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] If the line connecting them intersects the circle in two points, X and Y and the points are, in order, *X*, *P*, *Q*, *Y*.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] (the factor one half is needed to make the curvature −1).
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Since the cross-ratio is invariant under projective transformations, it follows that the hyperbolic distance is invariant under the projective transformations that preserve the conic C.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Conversely, the group G acts transitively on the set of pairs of points (*p*, *q*) in the unit disk at a fixed hyperbolic distance.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Later, partly through the influence of Henri Poincaré, the cross ratio of four complex numbers on a circle was used for hyperbolic metrics.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Being on a circle means the four points are the image of four real points under a Möbius transformation, and hence the cross ratio is a real number.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The Poincaré half-plane model and Poincaré disk model are two models of hyperbolic geometry in the complex projective line.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] These models are instances of Cayley–Klein metrics.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] We may consider the permutations of the four variables as an action of the symmetric group S4 on functions of the four variables.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Since the above four permutations leave the cross ratio unaltered, they form the stabilizer K of the cross-ratio under this action, and this induces an effective action of the quotient group $\mathrm {S} _{4}/K$ on the orbit of the cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The four permutations in K provide a realization of the Klein four-group in S4, and the quotient $\mathrm {S} _{4}/K$ is isomorphic to the symmetric group S3.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] As functions of $\lambda ,$ these are examples of Möbius transformations, which under composition of functions form the Mobius group PGL(2, **C**).
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The six transformations form a subgroup known as the **anharmonic group**, again isomorphic to S3.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] They are the torsion elements (elliptic transforms) in PGL(2, **C**).
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Namely, ${\textstyle {\tfrac {1}{\lambda }}}$ , $1-\lambda \,$ , and ${\textstyle {\tfrac {\lambda }{\lambda -1}}}$ are of order 2 with respective fixed points $-1,$ ${\textstyle {\tfrac {1}{2}},}$ and $2,$ (namely, the orbit of the harmonic cross-ratio).
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The order 2 elements exchange these two elements (as they do any pair other than their fixed points), and thus the action of the anharmonic group on $e^{\pm i\pi /3}$ gives the quotient map of symmetric groups $\mathrm {S} _{3}\to \mathrm {S} _{2}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Further, the fixed points of the individual 2-cycles are, respectively, $-1,$ ${\textstyle {\tfrac {1}{2}},}$ and $2,$ and this set is also preserved and permuted by the 3-cycles.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Geometrically, this can be visualized as the rotation group of the trigonal dihedron, which is isomorphic to the dihedral group of the triangle *D*3, as illustrated at right.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The anharmonic group is generated by ${\textstyle \lambda \mapsto {\tfrac {1}{\lambda }}}$ and ${\textstyle \lambda \mapsto 1-\lambda .}$ Its action on $\{0,1,\infty \}$ gives an isomorphism with S3.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] It may also be realised as the six Möbius transformations mentioned, which yields a projective representation of S3 over any field (since it is defined with integer entries), and is always faithful/injective (since no two terms differ only by 1/−1).
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Over the field with two elements, the projective line only has three points, so this representation is an isomorphism, and is the exceptional isomorphism $\mathrm {S} _{3}\approx \mathrm {PGL} (2,\mathbb {Z} _{2})$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In characteristic 3, this stabilizes the point $-1=[-1:1]$ , which corresponds to the orbit of the harmonic cross-ratio being only a single point, since ${\textstyle 2={\tfrac {1}{2}}=-1}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] For certain values of $\lambda$ there will be greater symmetry and therefore fewer than six possible values for the cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] These values of $\lambda$ correspond to fixed points of the action of S3 on the Riemann sphere (given by the above six functions); or, equivalently, those points with a non-trivial stabilizer in this permutation group.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The first set of fixed points is $\{0,1,\infty \}.$ However, the cross-ratio can never take on these values if the points A, B, C, and D are all distinct.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The second set of fixed points is ${\textstyle {\big \{}{-1},{\tfrac {1}{2}},2{\big \}}.}$ This situation is what is classically called the **harmonic cross-ratio**, and arises in projective harmonic conjugates.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In the real case, there are no other exceptional orbits.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In the complex case, the most symmetric cross-ratio occurs when $\lambda =e^{\pm i\pi /3}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] These are then the only two values of the cross-ratio, and these are acted on according to the sign of the permutation.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio is invariant under the projective transformations of the line.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In the case of a complex projective line, or the Riemann sphere, these transformations are known as Möbius transformations.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] These transformations form a group acting on the Riemann sphere, the Möbius group.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio is real if and only if the four points are either collinear or concyclic, reflecting the fact that every Möbius transformation maps generalized circles to generalized circles.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The action of the Möbius group is simply transitive on the set of triples of distinct points of the Riemann sphere: given any ordered triple of distinct points, $(z_{2},z_{3},z_{4})$ , there is a unique Möbius transformation $f(z)$ that maps it to the triple $(0,1,\infty )$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] An alternative explanation for the invariance of the cross-ratio is based on the fact that the group of projective transformations of a line is generated by the translations, the homotheties, and the multiplicative inversion.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] where a is a constant in the ground field $\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] for a non-zero constant b in $\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Therefore, the cross-ratio is invariant under the affine transformations.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] the affine line needs to be augmented by the point at infinity, denoted $\infty$ , forming the projective line $\mathrm {P} ^{1}(\mathbb {F} )$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Each affine mapping $f:\mathbb {F} \to \mathbb {F}$ can be uniquely extended to a mapping of $\mathrm {P} ^{1}(\mathbb {F} )$ into itself that fixes the point at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The projective group is generated by T and the affine mappings extended to $\mathrm {P} ^{1}(\mathbb {F} )$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] In the case $\mathbb {F} =\mathbb {C}$ , the complex plane, this results in the Möbius group.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Since the cross-ratio is also invariant under T , it is invariant under any projective mapping of $\mathrm {P} ^{1}(\mathbb {F} )$ into itself.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] This is an invariant of the 2-dimensional special conformal transformation such as inversion $x^{\mu }\rightarrow {\frac {x^{\mu }}{|x|^{2}}}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The concept of cross ratio only depends on the ring operations of addition, multiplication, and inversion (though inversion of a given element is not certain in a ring).
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] One approach to cross ratio interprets it as a homography that takes three designated points to 0, 1, and ∞.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Under restrictions having to do with inverses, it is possible to generate such a mapping with ring operations in the projective line over a ring.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross ratio of four points is the evaluation of this homography at the fourth point.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The theory takes on a differential calculus aspect as the four points are brought into proximity.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] This leads to the theory of the Schwarzian derivative, and more generally of projective connections.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] The cross-ratio does not generalize in a simple manner to higher dimensions, due to other geometric properties of configurations of points, notably collinearity – configuration spaces are more complicated, and distinct k-tuples of points are not in general position.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] Collinearity is not the only geometric property of configurations of points that must be maintained – for example, five points determine a conic, but six general points do not lie on a conic, so whether any 6-tuple of points lies on a conic is also a projective invariant.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] One can study orbits of points in general position – in the line "general position" is equivalent to being distinct, while in higher dimensions it requires geometric considerations, as discussed – but, as the above indicates, this is more complicated and less informative.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] However, a generalization to Riemann surfaces of positive genus exists, using the Abel–Jacobi map and theta functions.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] This is quantity is projective invariant, and any function invariant under the action of the $\mathrm {PGL} (n,K)$ can be retrieved as a function of the volume cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/cross-ratio] When $n=1$ , this retrieves the classical cross-ratio.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Two triangles are in perspective axially if corresponding sides of the triangles, when extended, meet at points on a line, called the *axis of perspectivity*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Two triangles are in perspective centrally if the lines which run through corresponding vertices of the triangles meet at a point, called the *center of perspectivity*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues's theorem states that the truth of the first condition is necessary and sufficient for the truth of the second.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] This intersection theorem is true in the usual Euclidean plane but special care needs to be taken in exceptional cases, as when a pair of sides are parallel, so that their "point of intersection" recedes to infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Commonly, to remove these exceptions, mathematicians "complete" the Euclidean plane by adding points at infinity, following Jean-Victor Poncelet.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues's theorem is true for the real projective plane and for any projective space defined arithmetically from a field or division ring; that includes any projective space of dimension greater than two or in which Pappus's theorem holds.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] However, there are many "non-Desarguesian planes", in which Desargues's theorem is false.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Denote the three vertices of one triangle by *a*, *b* and *c*, and those of the other triangle by *A*, *B* and *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Let the vertices of separate triangles be connected by lines.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Then lines *ab* and *AB* meet in a first point, lines *ac* and *AC* meet in a second point, and lines *bc* and *BC* meet in a third point.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] *Axial perspectivity* means these three points all lie on a common line called the *axis of perspectivity*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] *Central perspectivity* means that the three lines *Aa*, *Bb* and *Cc* are concurrent, at a point called the *center of perspectivity*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues never published this theorem, but it appeared in an appendix entitled *Universal Method of M.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues for Using Perspective* (*Manière universelle de M.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues pour practiquer la perspective*) to a practical book on the use of perspective published in 1648 by his friend and pupil Abraham Bosse (1602–1676).
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] The importance of Desargues's theorem in abstract projective geometry is due especially to the fact that a projective space satisfies that theorem if and only if it is isomorphic to a projective space defined over a field or division ring.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] In an affine space such as the Euclidean plane a similar statement is true, but only if one lists various exceptions involving parallel lines.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues's theorem is therefore one of the simplest geometric theorems whose natural home is in projective rather than affine space.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] By definition, two triangles are perspective if and only if they are in perspective centrally (or, equivalently according to this theorem, in perspective axially).
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Note that perspective triangles need not be similar.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Under the standard duality of plane projective geometry (where points correspond to lines and collinearity of points corresponds to concurrency of lines), the statement of Desargues's theorem is self-dual: axial perspectivity is translated into central perspectivity and vice versa.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] The Desargues configuration (below) is a self-dual configuration.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] This self-duality in the statement is due to the usual modern way of writing the theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Historically, the theorem only read, "In a projective space, a pair of centrally perspective triangles is axially perspective" and the dual of this statement was called the converse of Desargues's theorem and was always referred to by that name.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues's theorem holds for projective space of any dimension over any field or division ring, and also holds for abstract projective spaces of dimension at least 3.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] In dimension 2 the planes for which it holds are called Desarguesian planes and are the same as the planes that can be given coordinates over a division ring.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] There are also many non-Desarguesian planes where Desargues's theorem does not hold.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Desargues's theorem is true for any projective space of dimension at least 3, and more generally for any projective space that can be embedded in a space of dimension at least 3.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] The points *A*, *B*, *a* and *b* are coplanar (lie in the same plane) because of the assumed concurrency of *Aa* and *Bb*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Therefore, the lines *AB* and *ab* belong to the same plane and must intersect.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Further, if the two triangles lie on different planes, then the point *AB* ∩ *ab* belongs to both planes.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] By a symmetric argument, the points *AC* ∩ *ac* and *BC* ∩ *bc* also exist and belong to the planes of both triangles.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Since these two planes intersect in more than one point, their intersection is a line that contains all three points.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] This proves Desargues's theorem if the two triangles are not contained in the same plane.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] If they are in the same plane, Desargues's theorem can be proved by choosing a point not in the plane, using this to lift the triangles out of the plane so that the argument above works, and then projecting back into the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] The last step of the proof fails if the projective space has dimension less than 3, as in this case it is not possible to find a point not in the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Monge's theorem also asserts that three points lie on a line, and has a proof using the same idea of considering it in three rather than two dimensions and writing the line as an intersection of two planes.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] As there are non-Desarguesian projective planes in which Desargues's theorem is not true, some extra conditions need to be met in order to prove it.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] These conditions usually take the form of assuming the existence of sufficiently many collineations of a certain type, which in turn leads to showing that the underlying algebraic coordinate system must be a division ring (skewfield).
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] A plane in which Pappus's theorem is universally true is called *Pappian*.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Hessenberg (1905) showed that Desargues's theorem can be deduced from three applications of Pappus's theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] The converse of this result is not true, that is, not all Desarguesian planes are Pappian.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Satisfying Pappus's theorem universally is equivalent to having the underlying coordinate system be commutative.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] A plane defined over a non-commutative division ring (a division ring that is not a field) would therefore be Desarguesian but not Pappian.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] However, due to Wedderburn's little theorem, which states that all *finite* division rings are fields, all *finite* Desarguesian planes are Pappian.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] There is no known completely geometric proof of this fact, although Bamberg & Penttila (2015) give a proof that uses only "elementary" algebraic facts (rather than the full strength of Wedderburn's little theorem).
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Those ten points and ten lines make up the Desargues configuration, an example of a projective configuration.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] This restricted version states that if two triangles are perspective from a point on a given line, and two pairs of corresponding sides also meet on this line, then the third pair of corresponding sides meet on the line as well.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] Thus, it is the specialization of Desargues's Theorem to only the cases in which the center of perspectivity lies on the axis of perspectivity.
[src:projective-geometry/desargues-s-theorem] A Moufang plane is a projective plane in which the little Desargues theorem is valid for every line.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In projective geometry, **duality** or **plane duality** is a formalization of the striking symmetry of the roles played by points and lines in the definitions and theorems of projective planes.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] There are two approaches to the subject of duality, one through language (§ Principle of duality) and the other a more functional approach through special mappings.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] These are completely equivalent and either treatment has as its starting point the axiomatic version of the geometries under consideration.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In the functional approach there is a map between related geometries that is called a ***duality***.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Such a map can be constructed in many ways.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The concept of plane duality readily extends to *space duality* and beyond that to duality in any finite-dimensional projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A projective plane *C* may be defined axiomatically as an incidence structure, in terms of a set *P* of *points*, a set *L* of *lines*, and an incidence relation I that determines which points lie on which lines.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] These sets can be used to define a **plane dual structure**.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] *C*∗ is also a projective plane, called the **dual plane** of *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If *C* and *C*∗ are isomorphic, then *C* is called ***self-dual***.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The projective planes PG(2, *K*) for any field (or, more generally, for every division ring (skewfield) isomorphic to its dual) *K* are self-dual.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In particular, Desarguesian planes of finite order are always self-dual.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] However, there are non-Desarguesian planes which are not self-dual, such as the Hall planes and some that are, such as the Hughes planes.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In a projective plane a statement involving points, lines and incidence between them that is obtained from another such statement by interchanging the words "point" and "line" and making whatever grammatical adjustments that are necessary, is called the **plane dual statement** of the first.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The plane dual statement of "Two points are on a unique line" is "Two lines meet at a unique point".
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Forming the plane dual of a statement is known as *dualizing* the statement.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If a statement is true in a projective plane *C*, then the plane dual of that statement must be true in the dual plane *C*∗.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] This follows since dualizing each statement in the proof "in *C*" gives a corresponding statement of the proof "in *C*∗".
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The ***principle of plane duality*** says that dualizing any theorem in a self-dual projective plane *C* produces another theorem valid in *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The above concepts can be generalized to talk about space duality, where the terms "points" and "planes" are interchanged (and lines remain lines).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] This leads to the *principle of space duality*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] These principles provide a good reason for preferring to use a "symmetric" term for the incidence relation.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Thus instead of saying "a point lies on a line" one should say "a point is incident with a line" since dualizing the latter only involves interchanging point and line ("a line is incident with a point").
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The validity of the principle of plane duality follows from the axiomatic definition of a projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The three axioms of this definition can be written so that they are self-dual statements implying that the dual of a projective plane is also a projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The dual of a true statement in a projective plane is therefore a true statement in the dual projective plane and the implication is that for self-dual planes, the dual of a true statement in that plane is also a true statement in that plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] As the real projective plane, PG(2, **R**), is self-dual there are a number of pairs of well known results that are duals of each other.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Not only statements, but also systems of points and lines can be dualized.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A set of *m* points and *n* lines is called an (*m**c*, *n**d*) *configuration* if *c* of the *n* lines pass through each point and *d* of the *m* points lie on each line.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Thus, the dual of a quadrangle, a (43, 62) configuration of four points and six lines, is a quadrilateral, a (62, 43) configuration of six points and four lines.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The set of all points on a line, called a projective range, has as its dual a pencil of lines, the set of all lines on a point, in two dimensions, or a pencil of hyperplanes in higher dimensions.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A line segment on a projective line has as its dual the shape swept out by these lines or hyperplanes, a double wedge.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A **plane duality** is a map from a projective plane *C* = (*P*, *L*, I) to its *dual plane* *C*∗ = (*L*, *P*, I∗) (see § Principle of duality above) which preserves incidence.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] That is, a plane duality *σ* will map points to lines and lines to points (*P**σ* = *L* and *L**σ* = *P*) in such a way that if a point *Q* is on a line *m* (denoted by *Q* I *m*) then *Q* I *m* ⇔ *m**σ* I∗*Q**σ*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A plane duality which is an isomorphism is called a *correlation*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The existence of a correlation means that the projective plane *C* is *self-dual*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The projective plane *C* in this definition need not be a Desarguesian plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] However, if it is, that is, *C* = PG(2, *K*) with *K* a division ring (skewfield), then a duality, as defined below for general projective spaces, gives a plane duality on *C* that satisfies the above definition.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Consequently, a duality interchanges objects of dimension *r* with objects of dimension *n* − 1 − *r* ( = codimension *r* + 1).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] That is, in a projective space of dimension *n*, the points (dimension 0) correspond to hyperplanes (codimension 1), the lines joining two points (dimension 1) correspond to the intersection of two hyperplanes (codimension 2), and so on.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The *dual* *V*∗ of a finite-dimensional (right) vector space *V* over a skewfield *K* can be regarded as a (right) vector space of the same dimension over the opposite skewfield *K*o.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] There is thus an inclusion-reversing bijection between the projective spaces PG(*n*, *K*) and PG(*n*, *K*o).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If *K* and *K*o are isomorphic then there exists a duality on PG(*n*, *K*).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Conversely, if PG(*n*, *K*) admits a duality for *n* > 1, then *K* and *K*o are isomorphic.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let π be a duality of PG(*n*, *K*) for *n* > 1.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If π is composed with the natural isomorphism between PG(*n*, *K*) and PG(*n*, *K*o), the composition *θ* is an incidence preserving bijection between PG(*n*, *K*) and PG(*n*, *K*o).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] By the Fundamental theorem of projective geometry *θ* is induced by a semilinear map *T*: *V* → *V*∗ with associated isomorphism *σ*: *K* → *K*o, which can be viewed as an antiautomorphism of *K*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In the classical literature, π would be called a **reciprocity** in general, and if *σ* = id it would be called a **correlation** (and *K* would necessarily be a field).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Some authors suppress the role of the natural isomorphism and call *θ* a duality.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] When this is done, a duality may be thought of as a collineation between a pair of specially related projective spaces and called a reciprocity.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If this collineation is a projectivity then it is called a correlation.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let *T**w* = *T*(*w*) denote the linear functional of *V*∗ associated with the vector *w* in *V*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Any duality of PG(*n*, *K*) for *n* > 1 is induced by a nondegenerate sesquilinear form on the underlying vector space (with a companion antiautomorphism) and conversely.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Homogeneous coordinates may be used to give an algebraic description of dualities.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] To simplify this discussion we shall assume that *K* is a field, but everything can be done in the same way when *K* is a skewfield as long as attention is paid to the fact that multiplication need not be a commutative operation.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The points of PG(*n*, *K*) can be taken to be the nonzero vectors in the (*n* + 1)-dimensional vector space over *K*, where we identify two vectors which differ by a scalar factor.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Another way to put it is that the points of *n*-dimensional projective space are the 1-dimensional vector subspaces, which may be visualized as the lines through the origin in *K**n*+1.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Also the *n*- (vector) dimensional subspaces of *K**n*+1 represent the (*n* − 1)- (geometric) dimensional hyperplanes of projective *n*-space over *K*, i.e., PG(*n*, *K*).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] When a vector **u** is used to define a hyperplane in this way it shall be denoted by **u**H, while if it is designating a point we will use **u**P.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] They are referred to as *point coordinates* or *hyperplane coordinates* respectively (in the important two-dimensional case, hyperplane coordinates are called *line coordinates*).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Some authors distinguish how a vector is to be interpreted by writing hyperplane coordinates as horizontal (row) vectors while point coordinates are written as vertical (column) vectors.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A simple reciprocity (actually a correlation) can be given by **u**P ↔ **u**H between points and hyperplanes.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] This extends to a reciprocity between the line generated by two points and the intersection of two such hyperplanes, and so forth.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Specifically, in the projective plane, PG(2, *K*), with *K* a field, we have the correlation given by: points in homogeneous coordinates (*a*, *b*, *c*) ↔ lines with equations *ax* + *by* + *cz* = *0*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In a projective space, PG(3, *K*), a correlation is given by: points in homogeneous coordinates (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) ↔ planes with equations *ax* + *by* + *cz* + *dw* = 0.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] where the companion antiautomorphism *σ* = id.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] This is therefore a bilinear form (note that *K* must be a field).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] where *G* is the (*n* + 1) × (*n* + 1) identity matrix, using the convention that **u**H is a row vector and **x**P is a column vector.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] This correlation in the case of PG(2, **R**) can be described geometrically using the model of the real projective plane which is a "unit sphere with antipodes identified", or equivalently, the model of lines and planes through the origin of the vector space **R**3.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Associate to any line through the origin the unique plane through the origin which is perpendicular (orthogonal) to the line.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] When, in the model, these lines are considered to be the points and the planes the lines of the projective plane PG(2, **R**), this association becomes a correlation (actually a polarity) of the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The sphere model is obtained by intersecting the lines and planes through the origin with a unit sphere centered at the origin.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The lines meet the sphere in antipodal points which must then be identified to obtain a point of the projective plane, and the planes meet the sphere in great circles which are thus the lines of the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] That this association "preserves" incidence is most easily seen from the lines and planes model.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A point incident with a line in the projective plane corresponds to a line through the origin lying in a plane through the origin in the model.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Applying the association, the plane becomes a line through the origin perpendicular to the plane it is associated with.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] This image line is perpendicular to every line of the plane which passes through the origin, in particular the original line (point of the projective plane).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] All lines that are perpendicular to the original line at the origin lie in the unique plane which is orthogonal to the original line, that is, the image plane under the association.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Thus, the image line lies in the image plane and the association preserves incidence.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] As in the above example, matrices can be used to represent dualities.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let π be a duality of PG(*n*, *K*) for *n* > 1 and let *φ* be the associated sesquilinear form (with companion antiautomorphism *σ*) on the underlying (*n* + 1)-dimensional vector space *V*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] where *G* is a nonsingular (*n* + 1) × (*n* + 1) matrix over *K* and the vectors are written as column vectors.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The notation **x***σ* means that the antiautomorphism *σ* is applied to each coordinate of the vector **x**.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A duality that is an involution (has order two) is called a **polarity**.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] It is necessary to distinguish between polarities of general projective spaces and those that arise from the slightly more general definition of plane duality.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] It is also possible to give more precise statements in the case of a finite geometry, so we shall emphasize the results in finite projective planes.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If π is a duality of PG(*n*, *K*), with *K* a skewfield, then a common notation is defined by π(*S*) = *S*⊥ for a subspace *S* of PG(*n*, *K*).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Hence, a polarity is a duality for which *S*⊥⊥ = *S* for every subspace *S* of PG(*n*, *K*).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A duality is a polarity if and only if the (nondegenerate) sesquilinear form defining it is reflexive.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Polarities have been classified, a result of Birkhoff & von Neumann (1936) that has been reproven several times.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let *V* be a (left) vector space over the skewfield *K* and *φ* be a reflexive nondegenerate sesquilinear form on *V* with companion anti-automorphism *σ*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The polarity is called a **null polarity** (or a **symplectic polarity**) and can only exist when the projective dimension *n* is odd.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Such a polarity is called a **unitary polarity** (or a **Hermitian polarity**).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A point *P* of PG(*n*, *K*) is an **absolute point** (self-conjugate point) with respect to polarity ⊥ if *P* I *P*⊥.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Similarly, a hyperplane *H* is an **absolute hyperplane** (self-conjugate hyperplane) if *H*⊥ I *H*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Expressed in other terms, a point **x** is an absolute point of polarity π with associated sesquilinear form *φ* if *φ*(**x**, **x**) = 0 and if *φ* is written in terms of matrix *G*, **x**T *G* **x***σ* = 0.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The set of absolute points of each type of polarity can be described.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] We again restrict the discussion to the case that *K* is a field.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] All the points of the space PG(2*s* + 1, *K*) are absolute points of a null polarity.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The absolute points of a Hermitian polarity form a Hermitian variety, which may be empty if *K* is infinite.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] When composed with itself, the correlation *φ*(**x**P) = **x**H (in any dimension) produces the identity function, so it is a polarity.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Which points are in this point set depends on the field *K*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If *K* = **R** then the set is empty, there are no absolute points (and no absolute hyperplanes).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] On the other hand, if *K* = **C** the set of absolute points form a nondegenerate quadric (a conic in two-dimensional space).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If *K* is a finite field of odd characteristic the absolute points also form a quadric, but if the characteristic is even the absolute points form a hyperplane (this is an example of a pseudo polarity).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Under any duality, the point *P* is called the **pole** of the hyperplane *P*⊥, and this hyperplane is called the **polar** of the point *P*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Using this terminology, the absolute points of a polarity are the points that are incident with their polars and the absolute hyperplanes are the hyperplanes that are incident with their poles.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] By Wedderburn's theorem every finite skewfield is a field and an automorphism of order two (other than the identity) can only exist in a finite field whose order is a square.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] These facts help to simplify the general situation for finite Desarguesian planes.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If π is a polarity of the finite Desarguesian projective plane PG(2, *q*) where *q* = *p**e* for some prime *p*, then the number of absolute points of π is *q* + 1 if π is orthogonal or *q*3/2 + 1 if π is unitary.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In the orthogonal case, the absolute points lie on a conic if *p* is odd or form a line if *p* = 2.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The unitary case can only occur if *q* is a square; the absolute points and absolute lines form a unital.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In the general projective plane case where duality means *plane duality*, the definitions of polarity, absolute elements, pole and polar remain the same.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let **P** denote a projective plane of order *n*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The number of non-absolute points (lines) incident with a non-absolute line (point) is even.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The polarity π has at least *n* + 1 absolute points and if *n* is not a square, exactly *n* + 1 absolute points.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] 2. if *n* is even, the absolute points are collinear on a non-absolute line.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A polarity π in a projective plane of square order *n* = *s*2 has at most *s*3 + 1 absolute points.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Furthermore, if the number of absolute points is *s*3 + 1, then the absolute points and absolute lines form a unital (i.e., every line of the plane meets this set of absolute points in either 1 or *s* + 1 points).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A method that can be used to construct a polarity of the real projective plane has, as its starting point, a construction of a partial duality in the Euclidean plane.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In the Euclidean plane, fix a circle *C* with center *O* and radius *r*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] For each point *P* other than *O* define an image point *Q* so that *OP* ⋅ *OQ* = *r*2.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The mapping defined by *P* → *Q* is called **inversion** with respect to circle *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The line *p* through *Q* which is perpendicular to the line *OP* is called the **polar** of the point *P* with respect to circle *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let *q* be a line not passing through *O*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Drop a perpendicular from *O* to *q*, meeting *q* at the point *P* (this is the point of *q* that is closest to *O*).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The image *Q* of *P* under inversion with respect to *C* is called the **pole** of *q*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If a point *M* is on a line *q* (not passing through *O*) then the pole of *q* lies on the polar of *M* and vice versa.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The incidence preserving process, in which points and lines are transformed into their polars and poles with respect to *C* is called **reciprocation**.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] In order to turn this process into a correlation, the Euclidean plane (which is not a projective plane) needs to be expanded to the extended euclidean plane by adding a line at infinity and points at infinity which lie on this line.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The pole of the *x*-axis is the point of infinity of the vertical lines and the pole of the *y*-axis is the point of infinity of the horizontal lines.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The construction of a correlation based on inversion in a circle given above can be generalized by using inversion in a conic section (in the extended real plane).
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The correlations constructed in this manner are of order two, that is, polarities.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] We shall describe this polarity algebraically by following the above construction in the case that *C* is the unit circle (i.e., *r* = 1) centered at the origin.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The line passing through *Q* that is perpendicular to the line *OP* has equation *ax* + *by* = 1.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Switching to homogeneous coordinates using the embedding (*a*, *b*) ↦ (*a*, *b*, 1), the extension to the real projective plane is obtained by permitting the last coordinate to be 0.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Note that restricted to the Euclidean plane (that is, set *z* = 1) this is just the unit circle, the circle of inversion.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The theory of poles and polars of a conic in a projective plane can be developed without the use of coordinates and other metric concepts.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Let *C* be a conic in PG(2, *F*) where *F* is a field not of characteristic two, and let *P* be a point of this plane not on *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Two distinct secant lines to the conic, say *AB* and *JK* determine four points on the conic (*A*, *B*, *J*, *K*) that form a quadrangle.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The point *P* is a vertex of the diagonal triangle of this quadrangle.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The *polar* of *P* with respect to *C* is the side of the diagonal triangle opposite *P*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The theory of projective harmonic conjugates of points on a line can also be used to define this relationship.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] If a variable line through the point *P* is a secant of the conic *C*, the harmonic conjugates of *P* with respect to the two points of *C* on the secant all lie on the *polar* of *P*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] There are several properties that polarities in a projective plane have.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Given a polarity π, a point *P* lies on line *q*, the polar of point *Q* if and only if *Q* lies on *p*, the polar of *P*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Points *P* and *Q* that are in this relation are called **conjugate** points with respect to π.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Absolute points are called **self-conjugate** in keeping with this definition since they are incident with their own polars.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The line joining two self-conjugate points cannot be a self-conjugate line.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A line cannot contain more than two self-conjugate points.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A polarity induces an involution of conjugate points on any line that is not self-conjugate.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A triangle in which each vertex is the pole of the opposite side is called a **self-polar** triangle.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A correlation that maps the three vertices of a triangle to their opposite sides respectively is a polarity and this triangle is self-polar with respect to this polarity.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The principle of duality is due to Joseph Diaz Gergonne (1771−1859) a champion of the then emerging field of Analytic geometry and founder and editor of the first journal devoted entirely to mathematics, *Annales de mathématiques pures et appliquées*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Gergonne and Charles Julien Brianchon (1785−1864) developed the concept of plane duality.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Gergonne coined the terms "duality" and "polar" (but "pole" is due to F.-J.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Servois) and adopted the style of writing dual statements side by side in his journal.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Jean-Victor Poncelet (1788−1867) author of the first text on projective geometry, *Traité des propriétés projectives des figures*, was a synthetic geometer who systematically developed the theory of poles and polars with respect to a conic.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Poncelet maintained that the principle of duality was a consequence of the theory of poles and polars.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Julius Plücker (1801−1868) is credited with extending the concept of duality to three and higher dimensional projective spaces.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Poncelet and Gergonne started out as earnest but friendly rivals presenting their different points of view and techniques in papers appearing in *Annales de Gergonne*.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Antagonism grew over the issue of priority in claiming the principle of duality as their own.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] A young Plücker was caught up in this feud when a paper he had submitted to Gergonne was so heavily edited by the time it was published that Poncelet was misled into believing that Plücker had plagiarized him.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] The vitriolic attack by Poncelet was countered by Plücker with the support of Gergonne and ultimately the onus was placed on Gergonne.
[src:projective-geometry/duality-projective-geometry] Of this feud, Pierre Samuel has quipped that since both men were in the French army and Poncelet was a general while Gergonne a mere captain, Poncelet's view prevailed, at least among their French contemporaries.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In mathematics, **homogeneous coordinates** or **projective coordinates**, introduced by August Ferdinand Möbius in his 1827 work *Der barycentrische Calcul*, are a system of coordinates used in projective geometry, just as Cartesian coordinates are used in Euclidean geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] They have the advantage that the coordinates of points, including points at infinity, can be represented using finite coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Formulas involving homogeneous coordinates are often simpler and more symmetric than their Cartesian counterparts.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Homogeneous coordinates have a range of applications, including computer graphics and 3D computer vision, where they allow affine transformations and, in general, projective transformations to be easily represented by a matrix.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] They are also used in fundamental elliptic curve cryptography algorithms.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] If homogeneous coordinates of a point are multiplied by a non-zero scalar then the resulting coordinates represent the same point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Since homogeneous coordinates are also given to points at infinity, the number of coordinates required to allow this extension is one more than the dimension of the projective space being considered.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] For example, two homogeneous coordinates are required to specify a point on the projective line and three homogeneous coordinates are required to specify a point in the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The real projective plane can be thought of as the Euclidean plane with additional points added, which are called points at infinity, and are considered to lie on a new line, the line at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] There is a point at infinity corresponding to each direction (numerically given by the slope of a line), informally defined as the limit of a point that moves in that direction away from the origin.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Parallel lines in the Euclidean plane are said to intersect at a point at infinity corresponding to their common direction.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Given a point $(x,y)$ on the Euclidean plane, for any non-zero real number Z , the triple $(xZ,yZ,Z)$ is called a set of homogeneous coordinates for the point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] By this definition, multiplying the three homogeneous coordinates by a common, non-zero factor gives a new set of homogeneous coordinates for the same point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In particular, $(x,y,1)$ is such a system of homogeneous coordinates for the point $(x,y)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] For example, the Cartesian point $(1,2)$ can be represented in homogeneous coordinates as $(1,2,1)$ or $(2,4,2)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The original Cartesian coordinates are recovered by dividing the first two positions by the third.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Thus unlike Cartesian coordinates, a single point can be represented by infinitely many homogeneous coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The equation of a line through the origin $(0,0)$ may be written $nx+my=0$ where n and m are not both 0 .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In parametric form this can be written $x=mt,y=-nt$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Let $Z=1/t$ , so the coordinates of a point on the line may be written $(m/Z,-n/Z)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In homogeneous coordinates this becomes $(m,-n,Z)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In the limit, as t approaches infinity, in other words, as the point moves away from the origin, Z approaches 0 and the homogeneous coordinates of the point become $(m,-n,0)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Thus we define $(m,-n,0)$ as the homogeneous coordinates of the point at infinity corresponding to the direction of the line $nx+my=0$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] As any line of the Euclidean plane is parallel to a line passing through the origin, and since parallel lines have the same point at infinity, the infinite point on every line of the Euclidean plane has been given homogeneous coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The triple $(0,0,0)$ is omitted and does not represent any point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The origin of the Euclidean plane is represented by $(0,0,1)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Some authors use different notations for homogeneous coordinates which help distinguish them from Cartesian coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The use of colons instead of commas, for example $(x:y:z)$ instead of $(x,y,z)$ , emphasizes that the coordinates are to be considered ratios.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Square brackets, as in $[x,y,z]$ emphasize that multiple sets of coordinates are associated with a single point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Some authors use a combination of colons and square brackets, as in $[x:y:z]$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The discussion in the preceding section applies analogously to projective spaces other than the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] So the points on the projective line may be represented by pairs of coordinates $(x,y)$ , not both zero.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In this case, the point at infinity is $(1,0)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Similarly the points in projective n -space are represented by $(n+1)$ -tuples.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The use of real numbers gives homogeneous coordinates of points in the classical case of the real projective spaces, however any field may be used, in particular, the complex numbers may be used for complex projective space.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] For example, the complex projective line uses two homogeneous complex coordinates and is known as the Riemann sphere.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Other fields, including finite fields, can be used.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Homogeneous coordinates for projective spaces can also be created with elements from a division ring (a skew field).
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] However, in this case, care must be taken to account for the fact that multiplication may not be commutative.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] For the general ring *A*, a projective line over *A* can be defined with homogeneous factors acting on the left and the projective linear group acting on the right.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Another definition of the real projective plane can be given in terms of equivalence classes.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Then $\sim$ is an equivalence relation and the projective plane can be defined as the equivalence classes of $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\setminus \left\{0\right\}.$ If $(x,y,z)$ is one of the elements of the equivalence class p then these are taken to be homogeneous coordinates of p .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Lines in this space are defined to be sets of solutions of equations of the form $ax+by+cz=0$ where not all of a , b and c are zero.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Satisfaction of the condition $ax+by+cz=0$ depends only on the equivalence class of $(x,y,z),$ so the equation defines a set of points in the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The mapping $(x,y)\mapsto (x,y,1)$ defines an inclusion from the Euclidean plane to the projective plane and the complement of the image is the set of points with $z=0$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The equation $z=0$ is an equation of a line in the projective plane (see definition of a line in the projective plane), and is called the line at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The equivalence classes, p , are the lines through the origin with the origin removed.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The origin does not really play an essential part in the previous discussion so it can be added back in without changing the properties of the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] This produces a variation on the definition, namely the projective plane is defined as the set of lines in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ that pass through the origin and the coordinates of a non-zero element $(x,y,z)$ of a line are taken to be homogeneous coordinates of the line.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] These lines are now interpreted as points in the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Again, this discussion applies analogously to other dimensions.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] So the projective space of dimension n can be defined as the set of lines through the origin in $\mathbb {R} ^{n+1}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Homogeneous coordinates are not uniquely determined by a point, so a function defined on the coordinates, say $f(x,y,z)$ , does not determine a function defined on points as with Cartesian coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] But a condition $f(x,y,z)=0$ defined on the coordinates, as might be used to describe a curve, determines a condition on points if the function is homogeneous.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] If a set of coordinates represents the same point as $(x,y,z)$ then it can be written $(\lambda x,\lambda y,\lambda z)$ for some non-zero value of $\lambda$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The resulting function f is a polynomial, so it makes sense to extend its domain to triples where $z=0$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The equation $f(x,y,z)=0$ can then be thought of as the homogeneous form of $g(x,y)=0$ and it defines the same curve when restricted to the Euclidean plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The equation of a line in the projective plane may be given as $sx+ty+uz=0$ where s , t and u are constants.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Each triple $(s,t,u)$ determines a line, the line determined is unchanged if it is multiplied by a non-zero scalar, and at least one of s , t and u must be non-zero.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] So the triple $(s,t,u)$ may be taken to be homogeneous coordinates of a line in the projective plane, that is line coordinates as opposed to point coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] If in $sx+ty+uz=0$ the letters s , t and u are taken as variables and x , y and z are taken as constants then the equation becomes an equation of a set of lines in the space of all lines in the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Geometrically it represents the set of lines that pass through the point $(x,y,z)$ and may be interpreted as the equation of the point in line-coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In the same way, planes in 3-space may be given sets of four homogeneous coordinates, and so on for higher dimensions.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The same relation, $sx+ty+uz=0$ , may be regarded as either the equation of a line or the equation of a point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In general, there is no difference either algebraically or logically between homogeneous coordinates of points and lines.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] So plane geometry with points as the fundamental elements and plane geometry with lines as the fundamental elements are equivalent except for interpretation.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] This leads to the concept of duality in projective geometry, the principle that the roles of points and lines can be interchanged in a theorem in projective geometry and the result will also be a theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Analogously, the theory of points in projective 3-space is dual to the theory of planes in projective 3-space, and so on for higher dimensions.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Assigning coordinates to lines in projective 3-space is more complicated since it would seem that a total of 8 coordinates, either the coordinates of two points which lie on the line or two planes whose intersection is the line, are required.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The Plücker embedding is the generalization of this to create homogeneous coordinates of elements of any dimension m in a projective space of dimension n .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The homogeneous form for the equation of a circle in the real or complex projective plane is $x^{2}+y^{2}+2axz+2byz+cz^{2}=0$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The intersection of this curve with the line at infinity can be found by setting $z=0$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] This produces the equation $x^{2}+y^{2}=0$ which has two solutions over the complex numbers, giving rise to the points with homogeneous coordinates $(1,i,0)$ and $(1,-i,0)$ in the complex projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] These points are called the circular points at infinity and can be regarded as the common points of intersection of all circles.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] This can be generalized to curves of higher order as circular algebraic curves.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Just as the selection of axes in the Cartesian coordinate system is somewhat arbitrary, the selection of a single system of homogeneous coordinates out of all possible systems is somewhat arbitrary.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Therefore, it is useful to know how the different systems are related to each other.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Let $(x,y,z$ ) be homogeneous coordinates of a point in the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] So $(X,Y,Z)$ are a new system of homogeneous coordinates for the same point of the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Möbius's original formulation of homogeneous coordinates specified the position of a point as the center of mass (or barycenter) of a system of three point masses placed at the vertices of a fixed triangle.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Points within the triangle are represented by positive masses and points outside the triangle are represented by allowing negative masses.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Multiplying the masses in the system by a scalar does not affect the center of mass, so this is a special case of a system of homogeneous coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Let l , m and n be three lines in the plane and define a set of coordinates X , Y and Z of a point p as the signed distances from p to these three lines.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] These are called the *trilinear coordinates* of p with respect to the triangle whose vertices are the pairwise intersections of the lines.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Strictly speaking these are not homogeneous, since the values of X , Y and Z are determined exactly, not just up to proportionality.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] There is a linear relationship between them however, so these coordinates can be made homogeneous by allowing multiples of $(X,Y,Z)$ to represent the same point.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] More generally, X , Y and Z can be defined as constants p , r and q times the distances to l , m and n , resulting in a different system of homogeneous coordinates with the same triangle of reference.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] This is, in fact, the most general type of system of homogeneous coordinates for points in the plane if none of the lines is the line at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Homogeneous coordinate matrix transformation demonstration.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Adjust the numbers in the matrix to apply that transform to the image.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Homogeneous coordinates are ubiquitous in computer graphics because they allow common vector operations such as translation, rotation, scaling and perspective projection to be represented as a matrix by which the vector is multiplied.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] By the chain rule, any sequence of such operations can be multiplied out into a single matrix, allowing simple and efficient processing.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] By contrast, using Cartesian coordinates, translations and perspective projection cannot be expressed as matrix multiplications, though other operations can.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Modern OpenGL and Direct3D graphics cards take advantage of homogeneous coordinates to implement a vertex shader efficiently using vector processors with 4-element registers.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] For example, in perspective projection, a position in space is associated with the line from it to a fixed point called the *center of projection*.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] The point is then mapped to a plane by finding the point of intersection of that plane and the line.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] This produces an accurate representation of how a three-dimensional object appears to the eye.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] In the simplest situation, the center of projection is the origin and points are mapped to the plane $z=1$ , working for the moment in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] For a given point in space, $(x,y,z)$ , the point where the line and the plane intersect is $(x/z,y/z,1)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] Dropping the now superfluous z coordinate, this becomes $(x/z,y/z)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/homogeneous-coordinates] As a result, any perspective projection of space can be represented as a single matrix.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] These three points are the points of intersection of the "opposite" sides of the hexagon $AbCaBc$ .
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] It holds in a projective plane over any field, but fails for projective planes over any noncommutative division ring.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Projective planes in which the "theorem" is valid are called **pappian planes**.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] If one considers a pappian plane containing a hexagon as just described but with sides $Ab$ and $aB$ parallel and also sides $Bc$ and $bC$ parallel (so that the Pappus line u is the line at infinity), one gets the *affine version* of Pappus's theorem shown in the second diagram.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] If the Pappus line u and the lines $g,h$ have a point in common, one gets the so-called **little** version of Pappus's theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Pappus's theorem is a special case of Pascal's theorem for a conic—the limiting case when the conic degenerates into 2 straight lines.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Pascal's theorem is in turn a special case of the Cayley–Bacharach theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The Pappus configuration is the configuration of 9 lines and 9 points that occurs in Pappus's theorem, with each line meeting 3 of the points and each point meeting 3 lines.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] In general, the Pappus line does not pass through the point of intersection of $ABC$ and $abc$ .
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Since, in particular, the lines $Bc,bC,XY$ have the properties of the lines $x,y,z$ of the dual theorem, and collinearity of $X,Y,Z$ is equivalent to concurrence of $Bc,bC,XY$ , the dual theorem is therefore just the same as the theorem itself.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The Levi graph of the Pappus configuration is the Pappus graph, a bipartite distance-regular graph with 18 vertices and 27 edges.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] If the affine form of the statement can be proven, then the projective form of Pappus's theorem is proven, as the extension of a pappian plane to a projective plane is unique.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Because of the parallelity in an affine plane one has to distinct two cases: $g\not \parallel h$ and $g\parallel h$ .
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] From the parallelity of the lines $Bc,\;Cb$ one gets $b=({\tfrac {\delta }{\gamma }},0)$ and the parallelity of the lines $Ab,Ba$ yields $a=(\delta ,0)$ .
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Hence line $Ca$ has slope $-1$ and is parallel line $Ac$ .
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] So this last set of three lines is concurrent if all the other eight sets are because multiplication is commutative, so $pq=qp$ .
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The proof above also shows that for Pappus's theorem to hold for a projective space over a division ring it is both sufficient and necessary that the division ring is a (commutative) field.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] German mathematician Gerhard Hessenberg proved that Pappus's theorem implies Desargues's theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] In general, Pappus's theorem holds for some projective plane if and only if it is a projective plane over a commutative field.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The projective planes in which Pappus's theorem does not hold are Desarguesian projective planes over noncommutative division rings, and non-Desarguesian planes.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The proof is invalid if $C,c,X$ happen to be collinear.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] In that case an alternative proof can be provided, for example, using a different projective reference.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] are concurrent, that means: they have a point U in common.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The left diagram shows the projective version, the right one an affine version, where the points $G,H$ are points at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] If point U is on the line $GH$ than one gets the "dual little theorem" of Pappus' theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] If in the affine version of the dual "little theorem" point U is a point at infinity too, one gets Thomsen's theorem, a statement on 6 points on the sides of a triangle (see diagram).
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The Thomsen figure plays an essential role coordinatising an axiomatic defined projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The proof of the closure of Thomsen's figure is covered by the proof for the "little theorem", given above.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Because the statement of Thomsen's theorem (the closure of the figure) uses only the terms *connect, intersect* and *parallel*, the statement is affinely invariant, and one can introduce coordinates such that $P=(0,0),\;Q=(1,0),\;R=(0,1)$ (see right diagram).
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The starting point of the sequence of chords is $(0,\lambda ).$ One easily verifies the coordinates of the points given in the diagram, which shows: the last point coincides with the first point.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] What we call Pappus's Theorem is found in chapters 202, 206, 207, 209, and 211, also numbered as Propositions 134, 138, 139, 141, and 143, of Book VII of Pappus's *Collection*.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Lemma VIII is what is called above the affine version of Pappus's Theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] We are going to show $\varDelta Z\ ||\ \varGamma H.$ To do this, we draw BE, ΔΓ, and ZH.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The other lemmas are proved in terms of what today is known as the cross ratio of four collinear points.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The first of these, Lemma III, has the diagram below (which uses Pappus's lettering, with G for Γ, D for Δ, J for Θ, and L for Λ).
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Here three concurrent straight lines, AB, AG, and AD, are crossed by two lines, JB and JE, which concur at J.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] So we have shown that this is independent of the choice of the particular straight line JD that crosses the three straight lines that concur at A.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] In particular $(J,G;D,B)=(J,Z;H,E).$ It does not matter on which side of A the straight line JE falls.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] In particular, the situation may be as in the next diagram, which is the diagram for Lemma X.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Just as before, we have $(J,G;D,B)=(J,Z;H,E).$ Pappus does not explicitly prove this; but Lemma X is a converse, namely that if these two cross ratios are the same, and the straight lines BE and DH cross at A, then the points G, A, and Z must be collinear.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] What we showed originally can be written as $(J,\infty ;K,L)=(J,G;D,B),$ with ∞ taking the place of the (nonexistent) intersection of JK and AG.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] The diagram for Lemma XIII is the same, but BA and DG, extended, meet at N.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] That is, the points of intersection of the pairs of opposite sides of the hexagon ADEGBZ are collinear.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] Lemmas XV and XVII are that, if the point M is determined as the intersection of HK and BG, then the points A, M, and D are collinear.
[src:projective-geometry/pappus-s-hexagon-theorem] That is, the points of intersection of the pairs of opposite sides of the hexagon BEKHZG are collinear.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In mathematics, **projective geometry** is the study of geometric properties that are invariant with respect to projective transformations.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] This means that, compared to elementary Euclidean geometry, projective geometry has a different setting (*projective space*) and a selective set of basic geometric concepts.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The basic intuitions are that projective space has more points than Euclidean space, for a given dimension, and that geometric transformations are permitted that transform the extra points (called "points at infinity") to Euclidean points, and vice versa.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Properties meaningful for projective geometry are respected by this new idea of transformation, which is more radical in its effects than can be expressed by a transformation matrix and translations (the affine transformations).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The first issue for geometers is what kind of geometry is adequate for a novel situation.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Unlike in Euclidean geometry, the concept of an angle does not apply in projective geometry, because no measure of angles is invariant with respect to projective transformations, as is seen in perspective drawing from a changing perspective.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] One source for projective geometry was indeed the theory of perspective.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Another difference from elementary geometry is the way in which parallel lines can be said to meet in a point at infinity, once the concept is translated into projective geometry's terms.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Again this notion has an intuitive basis, such as railway tracks meeting at the horizon in a perspective drawing.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] See *Projective plane* for the basics of projective geometry in two dimensions.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] While the ideas were available earlier, projective geometry was mainly a development of the 19th century.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] This included the theory of complex projective space, the coordinates used (homogeneous coordinates) being complex numbers.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Several major types of more abstract mathematics (including invariant theory, the Italian school of algebraic geometry, and Felix Klein's Erlangen programme resulting in the study of the classical groups) were motivated by projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] It was also a subject with many practitioners for its own sake, as synthetic geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Another topic that developed from axiomatic studies of projective geometry is finite geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The topic of projective geometry is itself now divided into many research subtopics, two examples of which are projective algebraic geometry (the study of projective varieties) and projective differential geometry (the study of differential invariants of the projective transformations).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry is an elementary non-metrical form of geometry, meaning that it does not support any concept of distance.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In two dimensions it begins with the study of configurations of points and lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] That there is indeed some geometric interest in this sparse setting was first established by Desargues and others in their exploration of the principles of perspective art.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In higher dimensional spaces there are considered hyperplanes (that always meet), and other linear subspaces, which exhibit the principle of duality.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The simplest illustration of duality is in the projective plane, where the statements "two distinct points determine a unique line" (i.e. the line through them) and "two distinct lines determine a unique point" (i.e. their point of intersection) show the same structure as propositions.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry can also be seen as a geometry of constructions with a straight-edge alone, excluding compass constructions, common in straightedge and compass constructions.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] As such, there are no circles, no angles, no measurements, no parallels, and no concept of intermediacy (or "betweenness").
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] It was realised that the theorems that do apply to projective geometry are simpler statements.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For example, the different conic sections are all equivalent in (complex) projective geometry, and some theorems about circles can be considered as special cases of these general theorems.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] During the early 19th century the work of Jean-Victor Poncelet, Lazare Carnot and others established projective geometry as an independent field of mathematics.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Its rigorous foundations were addressed by Karl von Staudt and perfected by Italians Giuseppe Peano, Mario Pieri, Alessandro Padoa and Gino Fano during the late 19th century.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry, like affine and Euclidean geometry, can also be developed from the Erlangen program of Felix Klein; projective geometry is characterized by invariants under transformations of the projective group.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] After much work on the very large number of theorems in the subject, therefore, the basics of projective geometry became understood.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The incidence structure and the cross-ratio are fundamental invariants under projective transformations.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry can be modeled by the affine plane (or affine space) plus a line (hyperplane) "at infinity" and then treating that line (or hyperplane) as "ordinary".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] An algebraic model for doing projective geometry in the style of analytic geometry is given by homogeneous coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] On the other hand, axiomatic studies revealed the existence of non-Desarguesian planes, examples to show that the axioms of incidence can be modelled (in two dimensions only) by structures not accessible to reasoning through homogeneous coordinate systems.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In a foundational sense, projective geometry and ordered geometry are elementary since they each involve a minimal set of axioms and either can be used as the foundation for affine and Euclidean geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry is not "ordered" and so it is a distinct foundation for geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry is less restrictive than either Euclidean geometry or affine geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] It is an intrinsically non-metrical geometry, meaning that facts are independent of any metric structure.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Under the projective transformations, the incidence structure and the relation of projective harmonic conjugates are preserved.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] A projective range is the one-dimensional foundation.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry formalizes one of the central principles of perspective art: that parallel lines meet at infinity, and therefore are drawn that way.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In essence, a projective geometry may be thought of as an extension of Euclidean geometry in which the "direction" of each line is subsumed within the line as an extra "point", and in which a "horizon" of directions corresponding to coplanar lines is regarded as a "line".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Thus, two parallel lines meet on a horizon line by virtue of their incorporating the same direction.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Idealized directions are referred to as points at infinity, while idealized horizons are referred to as lines at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In turn, all these lines lie in the plane at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] However, infinity is a metric concept, so a purely projective geometry does not single out any points, lines or planes in this regard—those at infinity are treated just like any others.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For example, parallel and nonparallel lines need not be treated as separate cases; rather an arbitrary projective plane is singled out as the ideal plane and located "at infinity" using homogeneous coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Additional properties of fundamental importance include Desargues' Theorem and the Pappus's hexagon theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In projective spaces of dimension 3 or greater there is a construction that allows one to prove Desargues' Theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] But for dimension 2, it must be separately postulated.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Using Desargues' Theorem, combined with the other axioms, it is possible to define the basic operations of arithmetic, geometrically.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The resulting operations satisfy the axioms of a field – except that the commutativity of multiplication requires Pappus's hexagon theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry also includes a full theory of conic sections, a subject also extensively developed in Euclidean geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] There are advantages to being able to think of a hyperbola and an ellipse as distinguished only by the way the hyperbola *lies across the line at infinity*; and that a parabola is distinguished only by being tangent to the same line.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The whole family of circles can be considered as *conics passing through two given points on the line at infinity* — at the cost of requiring complex coordinates.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Since coordinates are not "synthetic", one replaces them by fixing a line and two points on it, and considering the *linear system* of all conics passing through those points as the basic object of study.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] This method proved very attractive to talented geometers, and the topic was studied thoroughly.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] An example of this method is the multi-volume treatise by H.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The first geometrical properties of a projective nature were discovered during the 3rd century by Pappus of Alexandria.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Filippo Brunelleschi (1404–1472) started investigating the geometry of perspective during 1425 (see *Perspective (graphical) § History* for a more thorough discussion of the work in the fine arts that motivated much of the development of projective geometry).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Johannes Kepler (1571–1630) and Girard Desargues (1591–1661) independently developed the concept of the "point at infinity".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Desargues developed an alternative way of constructing perspective drawings by generalizing the use of vanishing points to include the case when these are infinitely far away.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] He made Euclidean geometry, where parallel lines are truly parallel, into a special case of an all-encompassing geometric system.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Desargues's study on conic sections drew the attention of 16-year-old Blaise Pascal and helped him formulate Pascal's theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The works of Gaspard Monge at the end of 18th and beginning of 19th century were important for the subsequent development of projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The work of Desargues was ignored until Michel Chasles chanced upon a handwritten copy during 1845.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Meanwhile, Jean-Victor Poncelet had published the foundational treatise on projective geometry during 1822.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Poncelet examined the projective properties of objects (those invariant under central projection) and, by basing his theory on the concrete pole and polar relation with respect to a circle, established a relationship between metric and projective properties.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The non-Euclidean geometries discovered soon thereafter were eventually demonstrated to have models, such as the Klein model of hyperbolic space, relating to projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Möbius wrote an article about permutations, now called Möbius transformations, of generalised circles in the complex plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] These transformations represent projectivities of the complex projective line.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The distance between points is given by a Cayley–Klein metric, known to be invariant under the translations since it depends on cross-ratio, a key projective invariant.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The translations are described variously as isometries in metric space theory, as linear fractional transformations formally, and as projective linear transformations of the projective linear group, in this case SU(1, 1).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The work of Poncelet, Jakob Steiner and others was not intended to extend analytic geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Techniques were supposed to be *synthetic*: in effect projective space as now understood was to be introduced axiomatically.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] As a result, reformulating early work in projective geometry so that it satisfies current standards of rigor can be somewhat difficult.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Even in the case of the projective plane alone, the axiomatic approach can result in models not describable via linear algebra.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] This period in geometry was overtaken by research on the general algebraic curve by Clebsch, Riemann, Max Noether and others, which stretched existing techniques, and then by invariant theory.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Towards the end of the century, the Italian school of algebraic geometry (Enriques, Segre, Severi) broke out of the traditional subject matter into an area demanding deeper techniques.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] During the later part of the 19th century, the detailed study of projective geometry became less fashionable, although the literature is voluminous.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Some important work was done in enumerative geometry in particular, by Schubert, that is now considered as anticipating the theory of Chern classes, taken as representing the algebraic topology of Grassmannians.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometry later proved key to Paul Dirac's invention of quantum mechanics.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] At a foundational level, the discovery that quantum measurements could fail to commute had disturbed and dissuaded Heisenberg, but past study of projective planes over noncommutative rings had likely desensitized Dirac.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In more advanced work, Dirac used extensive drawings in projective geometry to understand the intuitive meaning of his equations, before writing up his work in an exclusively algebraic formalism.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] There are many projective geometries, which may be divided into discrete and continuous: a *discrete* geometry comprises a set of points, which may or may not be *finite* in number, while a *continuous* geometry has infinitely many points with no gaps in between.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The only projective geometry of dimension 0 is a single point.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] A projective geometry of dimension 1 consists of a single line containing at least 3 points.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The geometric construction of arithmetic operations cannot be performed in either of these cases.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For dimension 2, there is a rich structure in virtue of the absence of Desargues' Theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The affine coordinates in a Desarguesian plane for the points designated to be the points at infinity (in this example: C, E and G) can be defined in several other ways.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Thus, the example having only 7 points is written PG(2, 2).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The fundamental property that singles out all projective geometries is the *elliptic* incidence property that any two distinct lines L and M in the projective plane intersect at exactly one point P.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The special case in analytic geometry of *parallel* lines is subsumed in the smoother form of a line *at infinity* on which P lies.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The *line at infinity* is thus a line like any other in the theory: it is in no way special or distinguished.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] (In the later spirit of the Erlangen programme one could point to the way the group of transformations can move any line to the *line at infinity*).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The parallel property of elliptic geometry is the key idea that leads to the principle of projective duality, possibly the most important property that all projective geometries have in common.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Similarly in 3 dimensions, the duality relation holds between points and planes, allowing any theorem to be transformed by swapping *point* and *plane*, *is contained by* and *contains*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] More generally, for projective spaces of dimension N, there is a duality between the subspaces of dimension *R* and dimension *N* − *R* − 1.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For *N* = 2, this specializes to the most commonly known form of duality—that between points and lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The duality principle was also discovered independently by Jean-Victor Poncelet.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] To establish duality only requires establishing theorems which are the dual versions of the axioms for the dimension in question.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In practice, the principle of duality allows us to set up a *dual correspondence* between two geometric constructions.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The most famous of these is the polarity or reciprocity of two figures in a conic curve (in 2 dimensions) or a quadric surface (in 3 dimensions).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] A commonplace example is found in the reciprocation of a symmetrical polyhedron in a concentric sphere to obtain the dual polyhedron.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Another example is Brianchon's theorem, the dual of the already mentioned Pascal's theorem, and one of whose proofs simply consists of applying the principle of duality to Pascal's.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Any given geometry may be deduced from an appropriate set of axioms.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Projective geometries are characterised by the "elliptic parallel" axiom, that *any two planes always meet in just one line*, or in the plane, *any two lines always meet in just one point*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In other words, there are no such things as parallel lines or planes in projective geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Many alternative sets of axioms for projective geometry have been proposed (see, for example, Coxeter 2003, Hilbert & Cohn-Vossen 1999, Greenberg 2008).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] These axioms are based on Whitehead, "The Axioms of Projective Geometry".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] There are two types, points and lines, and one "incidence" relation between points and lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The reason each line is assumed to contain at least 3 points is to eliminate some degenerate cases.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The spaces satisfying these three axioms either have at most one line, or are projective spaces of some dimension over a division ring, or are non-Desarguesian planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] One can add further axioms restricting the dimension or the coordinate ring.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For example, Coxeter's *Projective Geometry* references Veblen and Young in the three axioms above, together with a further 5 axioms that make the dimension 3 and the coordinate ring a commutative field of characteristic not 2.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] One can pursue axiomatization by postulating a ternary relation, [ABC] to denote when three points (not all necessarily distinct) are collinear.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For two distinct points, A and B, the line AB is defined as consisting of all points C for which [ABC].
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The axioms C0 and C1 then provide a formalization of G2; C2 for G1 and C3 for G3.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The concept of line generalizes to planes and higher-dimensional subspaces.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] A subspace, AB...XY may thus be recursively defined in terms of the subspace AB...X as that containing all the points of all lines YZ, as Z ranges over AB...X.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Collinearity then generalizes to the relation of "independence".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] A set {A, B, ..., Z} of points is independent, [AB...Z] if {A, B, ..., Z} is a minimal generating subset for the subspace AB...Z.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The projective axioms may be supplemented by further axioms postulating limits on the dimension of the space.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The minimum dimension is determined by the existence of an independent set of the required size.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For the lowest dimensions, the relevant conditions may be stated in equivalent form as follows.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The maximum dimension may also be determined in a similar fashion.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] For the lowest dimensions, they take on the following forms.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] It is a general theorem (a consequence of axiom (3)) that all coplanar lines intersect—the very principle that projective geometry was originally intended to embody.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Therefore, property (M3) may be equivalently stated that all lines intersect one another.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] It is generally assumed that projective spaces are of at least dimension 2.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In some cases, if the focus is on projective planes, a variant of M3 may be postulated.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Axiom (3) becomes vacuously true under (M3) and is therefore not needed in this context.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In incidence geometry, most authors give a treatment that embraces the Fano plane PG(2, 2) as the smallest finite projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The restricted planes given in this manner more closely resemble the real projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Given three non-collinear points, there are three lines connecting them, but with four points, no three collinear, there are six connecting lines and three additional "diagonal points" determined by their intersections.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The science of projective geometry captures this surplus determined by four points through a quaternary relation and the projectivities which preserve the complete quadrangle configuration.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] An harmonic quadruple of points on a line occurs when there is a complete quadrangle two of whose diagonal points are in the first and third position of the quadruple, and the other two positions are points on the lines joining two quadrangle points through the third diagonal point.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] A spatial perspectivity of a projective configuration in one plane yields such a configuration in another, and this applies to the configuration of the complete quadrangle.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Thus harmonic quadruples are preserved by perspectivity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] If one perspectivity follows another the configurations follow along.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The composition of two perspectivities is no longer a perspectivity, but a **projectivity**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] While corresponding points of a perspectivity all converge at a point, this convergence is *not* true for a projectivity that is *not* a perspectivity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] In projective geometry the intersection of lines formed by corresponding points of a projectivity in a plane are of particular interest.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The set of such intersections is called a **projective conic**, and in acknowledgement of the work of Jakob Steiner, it is referred to as a Steiner conic.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Given a conic *C* and a point *P* not on it, two distinct secant lines through *P* intersect *C* in four points.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] These four points determine a quadrangle of which *P* is a diagonal point.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] The line through the other two diagonal points is called the polar of *P* and *P*is the **pole** of this line.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-geometry] Alternatively, the polar line of *P* is the set of projective harmonic conjugates of *P* on a variable secant line passing through *P* and *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In mathematics, a **projective plane** is a geometric structure that extends the concept of a plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In the ordinary Euclidean plane, two lines typically intersect at a single point, but there are some pairs of lines (namely, parallel lines) that do not intersect.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A projective plane can be thought of as an ordinary plane equipped with additional "points at infinity" where parallel lines intersect.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Thus *any* two distinct lines in a projective plane intersect at exactly one point.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Renaissance artists, in developing the techniques of drawing in perspective, laid the groundwork for this mathematical topic.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The archetypical example is the real projective plane, also known as the **extended Euclidean plane**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This example, in slightly different guises, is important in algebraic geometry, topology and projective geometry where it may be denoted variously by PG(2, **R**), **RP**2, or **P**2(**R**), among other notations.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] There are many other projective planes, both infinite, such as the complex projective plane, and finite, such as the Fano plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A projective plane is a 2-dimensional projective space.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Not all projective planes can be embedded in 3-dimensional projective spaces; such embeddability is a consequence of a property known as Desargues' theorem, not shared by all projective planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Given any two distinct lines, there is exactly one point incident with both of them.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] There are four points such that no line is incident with more than two of them.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The second condition means that there are no parallel lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The last condition excludes the so-called ***degenerate*** cases (see below).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The term "incidence" is used to emphasize the symmetric nature of the relationship between points and lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Thus the expression "point *P* is incident with line *ℓ*" is used instead of either "*P* is on *ℓ*" or "*ℓ* passes through *P*".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It follows from the definition that the number of points $s+1$ incident with any given line in a projective plane is the same as the number of lines incident with any given point.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The (possibly infinite) cardinal number s is called **order** of the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Add a new line, which is considered incident with all the points at infinity (and no other points).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This line is called *the* *line at infinity*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The extended structure is a projective plane and is called the **extended Euclidean plane** or the real projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The process outlined above, used to obtain it, is called "projective completion" or *projectivization*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This plane can also be constructed by starting from **R**3 viewed as a vector space, see *§ Vector space construction* below.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The points of the Moulton plane are the points of the Euclidean plane, with coordinates in the usual way.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] To create the Moulton plane from the Euclidean plane some of the lines are redefined.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] That is, some of their point sets will be changed, but other lines will remain unchanged.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The Moulton plane has parallel classes of lines and is an affine plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It can be projectivized, as in the previous example, to obtain the **projective Moulton plane**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Desargues's theorem is not a valid theorem in either the Moulton plane or the projective Moulton plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This example has just thirteen points and thirteen lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The incidence relation (which points are on which lines) can be given by the following incidence matrix.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The rows are labelled by the points and the columns are labelled by the lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A 1 in row *i* and column *j* means that the point P*i* is on the line m*j*, while a 0 (which we represent here by a blank cell for ease of reading) means that they are not incident.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The matrix is in Paige–Wexler normal form.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Among many possibilities, the points P1, P4, P5, and P8, for example, will satisfy the third condition.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This example is known as the **projective plane of order three**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Though the line at infinity of the extended real plane may appear to have a different nature than the other lines of that projective plane, this is not the case.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Another construction of the same projective plane shows that no line can be distinguished (on geometrical grounds) from any other.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In this construction, each "point" of the real projective plane is the one-dimensional subspace (a *geometric* line) through the origin in a 3-dimensional vector space, and a "line" in the projective plane arises from a (*geometric*) plane through the origin in the 3-space.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This idea can be generalized and made more precise as follows.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Let *K* be any division ring (skewfield).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Let *K*3 denote the set of all triples *x* = (*x*0, *x*1, *x*2) of elements of *K* (a Cartesian product viewed as a vector space).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Similarly, let *x* and *y* be linearly independent elements of *K*3, meaning that *kx* + *my* = 0 implies that *k* = *m* = 0.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This 2-dimensional subspace contains various 1-dimensional subspaces through the origin that may be obtained by fixing *k* and *m* and taking the multiples of the resulting vector.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Different choices of *k* and *m* that are in the same ratio will give the same line.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The **projective plane** over *K*, denoted PG(2, *K*) or *K***P**2, has a set of *points* consisting of all the 1-dimensional subspaces in *K*3.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A subset *L* of the points of PG(2, *K*) is a *line* in PG(2, *K*) if there exists a 2-dimensional subspace of *K*3 whose set of 1-dimensional subspaces is exactly *L*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Verifying that this construction produces a projective plane is usually left as a linear algebra exercise.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] An alternate (algebraic) view of this construction is as follows.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Lines in the projective plane are defined exactly as above.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The coordinates (*x*0, *x*1, *x*2) of a point in PG(2, *K*) are called **homogeneous coordinates**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Each triple (*x*0, *x*1, *x*2) represents a well-defined point in PG(2, *K*), except for the triple (0, 0, 0), which represents no point.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Each point in PG(2, *K*), however, is represented by many triples.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If *K* is a topological space, then *K***P**2 inherits a topology via the product, subspace, and quotient topologies.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The real projective plane **RP**2 arises when *K* is taken to be the real numbers, **R**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] As a closed, non-orientable real 2-manifold, it serves as a fundamental example in topology.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In this construction, consider the unit sphere centered at the origin in **R**3.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Each of the **R**3 lines in this construction intersects the sphere at two antipodal points.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Since the **R**3 line represents a point of **RP**2, we will obtain the same model of **RP**2 by identifying the antipodal points of the sphere.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The lines of **RP**2 will be the great circles of the sphere after this identification of antipodal points.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This description gives the standard model of elliptic geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The complex projective plane **CP**2 arises when *K* is taken to be the complex numbers, **C**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It is a closed complex 2-manifold, and hence a closed, orientable real 4-manifold.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It and projective planes over other fields (known as **pappian planes**) serve as fundamental examples in algebraic geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The quaternionic projective plane **HP**2 is also of independent interest.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] By Wedderburn's Theorem, a finite division ring must be commutative and so be a field.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Thus, the finite examples of this construction are known as "field planes".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Taking *K* to be the finite field of *q* = *p**n* elements with prime *p* produces a projective plane of *q*2 + *q* + 1 points.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The field planes are usually denoted by PG(2, *q*) where PG stands for projective geometry, the "2" is the dimension and *q* is called the **order** of the plane (it is one less than the number of points on any line).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The Fano plane, discussed below, is denoted by PG(2, 2).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The third example above is the projective plane PG(2, 3).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The Fano plane is the projective plane arising from the field of two elements.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It is the smallest projective plane, with only seven points and seven lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In the figure at right, the seven points are shown as small balls, and the seven lines are shown as six line segments and a circle.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] However, one could equivalently consider the balls to be the "lines" and the line segments and circle to be the "points" – this is an example of duality in the projective plane: if the lines and points are interchanged, the result is still a projective plane (see below).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A permutation of the seven points that carries collinear points (points on the same line) to collinear points is called a *collineation* or *symmetry* of the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The collineations of a geometry form a group under composition, and for the Fano plane this group (PΓL(3, 2) = PGL(3, 2)) has 168 elements.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The theorem of Desargues is universally valid in a projective plane if and only if the plane can be constructed from a three-dimensional vector space over a skewfield as above.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] These planes are called **Desarguesian planes**, named after Girard Desargues.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The real (or complex) projective plane and the projective plane of order 3 given above are examples of Desarguesian projective planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The projective planes that can not be constructed in the preceding manner are called non-Desarguesian planes, and the Moulton plane given above is an example of one.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Many such finite and infinite planes are known.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The PG(2, *K*) notation is reserved for Desarguesian planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] When *K* is a field, a very common case, they are also known as *field planes* and if the field is a finite field they can be called *Galois planes*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] (Bruck 1955) proves the following theorem.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Let Π be a finite projective plane of order *N* with a proper subplane Π0 of order *M*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A finite Desarguesian projective plane of order q admits Baer subplanes (all necessarily Desarguesian) if and only if q is square; in this case the order of the Baer subplanes is ${\sqrt {q}}$ .
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In the finite Desarguesian planes PG(2, *pn*), the subplanes have orders which are the orders of the subfields of the finite field GF(*pn*), that is, *pi* where *i* is a divisor of *n*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In non-Desarguesian planes however, Bruck's theorem gives the only information about subplane orders.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The case of equality in the inequality of this theorem is not known to occur.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Whether or not there exists a subplane of order *M* in a plane of order *N* with *M*2 + *M* = *N* is an open question.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If such subplanes existed there would be projective planes of composite (non-prime power) order.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A **Fano subplane** is a subplane isomorphic to PG(2, 2), the unique projective plane of order 2.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If you consider a *quadrangle* (a set of 4 points no three collinear) in this plane, the points determine six of the lines of the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The remaining three points (called the *diagonal points* of the quadrangle) are the points where the lines that do not intersect at a point of the quadrangle meet.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The seventh line consists of all the diagonal points (usually drawn as a circle or semicircle).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In finite desarguesian planes, PG(2, *q*), Fano subplanes exist if and only if *q* is even (that is, a power of 2).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The situation in non-desarguesian planes is unsettled.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] They could exist in any non-desarguesian plane of order greater than 6, and indeed, they have been found in all non-desarguesian planes in which they have been looked for (in both odd and even orders).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] An open question, apparently due to Hanna Neumann though not published by her, is: Does every non-desarguesian plane contain a Fano subplane?
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If every quadrangle in a finite projective plane has collinear diagonal points, then the plane is desarguesian (of even order).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Projectivization of the Euclidean plane produced the real projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The inverse operation—starting with a projective plane, remove one line and all the points incident with that line—produces an **affine plane**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Given any line *l* and any point *P* not incident with *l*, there is exactly one line incident with *P* that does not meet *l*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The second condition means that there are parallel lines and is known as Playfair's axiom.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The expression "does not meet" in this condition is shorthand for "there does not exist a point incident with both lines".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The Euclidean plane and the Moulton plane are examples of infinite affine planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A finite projective plane will produce a finite affine plane when one of its lines and the points on it are removed.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The **order** of a finite affine plane is the number of points on any of its lines (this will be the same number as the order of the projective plane from which it comes).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The affine planes which arise from the projective planes PG(2, *q*) are denoted by AG(2, *q*).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] There is a projective plane of order *N* if and only if there is an affine plane of order *N*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] When there is only one affine plane of order *N* there is only one projective plane of order *N*, but the converse is not true.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The affine planes formed by the removal of different lines of the projective plane will be isomorphic if and only if the removed lines are in the same orbit of the collineation group of the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] These statements hold for infinite projective planes as well.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The complement of the image is the set of points of the form (0, *x*1, *x*2).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] From the point of view of the embedding just given, these points are the points at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The points at infinity are the "extra" points where parallel lines intersect in the construction of the extended real plane; the point (0, *x*1, *x*2) is where all lines of slope *x*2 / *x*1 intersect.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] These lines have slope 0 and do not intersect.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] They can be regarded as subsets of *K***P**2 via the embedding above, but these subsets are not lines in *K***P**2.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The projective lines ū and ȳ intersect at (0, 1, 0).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In fact, all lines in *K*2 of slope 0, when projectivized in this manner, intersect at (0, 1, 0) in *K***P**2.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The embedding of *K*2 into *K***P**2 given above is not unique.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Each embedding produces its own notion of points at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] has as its complement those points of the form (*x*0, 0, *x*2), which are then regarded as points at infinity.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] When an affine plane does not have the form of *K*2 with *K* a division ring, it can still be embedded in a projective plane, but the construction used above does not work.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A commonly used method for carrying out the embedding in this case involves expanding the set of affine coordinates and working in a more general "algebra".
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] One can construct a coordinate "ring"—a so-called planar ternary ring (not a genuine ring)—corresponding to any projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A planar ternary ring need not be a field or division ring, and there are many projective planes that are not constructed from a division ring.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] They are called non-Desarguesian projective planes and are an active area of research.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The Cayley plane (**OP**2), a projective plane over the octonions, is one of these because the octonions do not form a division ring.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Conversely, given a planar ternary ring (*R*, *T*), a projective plane can be constructed (see below).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A projective plane may be associated with several non-isomorphic planar ternary rings.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] When the set of coordinates of a projective plane actually form a ring, a linear ternary operator may be defined in this way, using the ring operations on the right, to produce a planar ternary ring.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Algebraic properties of this planar ternary coordinate ring turn out to correspond to geometric incidence properties of the plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] For example, Desargues' theorem corresponds to the coordinate ring being obtained from a division ring, while Pappus's theorem corresponds to this ring being obtained from a commutative field.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A projective plane satisfying Pappus's theorem universally is called a *Pappian plane*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Alternative, not necessarily associative, division algebras like the octonions correspond to Moufang planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] There is no known purely geometric proof of the purely geometric statement that Desargues' theorem implies Pappus' theorem in a finite projective plane (finite Desarguesian planes are Pappian).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] is the ternary operator of the planar ternary ring.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] For example, for *N* = 2 we can use the symbols {0, 1} associated with the finite field of order 2.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Degenerate planes do not fulfill the third condition in the definition of a projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] They are not structurally complex enough to be interesting in their own right, but from time to time they arise as special cases in general arguments.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] There are seven kinds of degenerate plane according to (Albert & Sandler 1968).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] 7. a point *P* not incident with a line *m*, an arbitrary (can be empty) collection of lines all incident with *P* and all the points of intersection of these lines with *m*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] These seven cases are not independent, the fourth and fifth can be considered as special cases of the sixth, while the second and third are special cases of the fourth and fifth respectively.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The special case of the seventh plane with no additional lines can be seen as an eighth plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A collineation of a projective plane is a bijective map of the plane to itself which maps points to points and lines to lines that preserves incidence, meaning that if *σ* is a bijection and point *P* is on line *m*, then *P**σ* is on *m**σ*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If *σ* is a collineation of a projective plane, a point *P* with *P* = *P**σ* is called a ***fixed point*** of *σ*, and a line *m* with *m* = *m**σ* is called a ***fixed line*** of *σ*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The points on a fixed line need not be fixed points, their images under *σ* are just constrained to lie on this line.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The collection of fixed points and fixed lines of a collineation form a ***closed configuration***, which is a system of points and lines that satisfy the first two but not necessarily the third condition in the definition of a projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Thus, the fixed point and fixed line structure for any collineation either form a projective plane by themselves, or a degenerate plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Collineations whose fixed structure forms a plane are called ***planar collineations***.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A **homography** (or *projective transformation*) of PG(2, *K*) is a collineation of this type of projective plane which is a linear transformation of the underlying vector space.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Using homogeneous coordinates they can be represented by invertible 3 × 3 matrices over *K* which act on the points of PG(2, *K*) by *y* = *M* *x*T, where *x* and *y* are points in *K*3 (vectors) and *M* is an invertible 3 × 3 matrix over *K*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Two matrices represent the same projective transformation if one is a constant multiple of the other.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Thus the group of projective transformations is the quotient of the general linear group by the scalar matrices called the projective linear group.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Another type of collineation of PG(2, *K*) is induced by any automorphism of *K*, these are called **automorphic collineations**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If *α* is an automorphism of *K*, then the collineation given by (*x*0, *x*1, x2) → (*x*0*α*, *x*1*α*, *x*2*α*) is an automorphic collineation.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The fundamental theorem of projective geometry says that all the collineations of PG(2, *K*) are compositions of homographies and automorphic collineations.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Automorphic collineations are planar collineations.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A projective plane is defined axiomatically as an incidence structure, in terms of a set *P* of points, a set *L* of lines, and an incidence relation *I* that determines which points lie on which lines.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] As *P* and *L* are only sets one can interchange their roles and define a **plane dual structure**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] where *I** is the converse relation of *I*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The plane dual statement of "Two points are on a unique line." is "Two lines meet at a unique point." Forming the plane dual of a statement is known as *dualizing* the statement.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If a statement is true in a projective plane *C*, then the plane dual of that statement must be true in the dual plane *C**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In the projective plane *C*, it can be shown that there exist four lines, no three of which are concurrent.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Dualizing this theorem and the first two axioms in the definition of a projective plane shows that the plane dual structure *C** is also a projective plane, called the **dual plane** of *C*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If *C* and *C** are isomorphic, then *C* is called ***self-dual***.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The projective planes PG(2, *K*) for any division ring *K* are self-dual.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A **duality** is a map from a projective plane *C* = (*P*, *L*, *I*) to its dual plane *C** = (*L*, *P*, *I**) (see above) which preserves incidence.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] That is, a duality *σ* will map points to lines and lines to points (*P**σ* = *L* and *L**σ* = *P*) in such a way that if a point *Q* is on a line *m* (denoted by *Q* *I* *m*) then *Q**σ* *I** *m**σ* ⇔ *m**σ* *I* *Q**σ*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A duality which is an isomorphism is called a **correlation**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If a correlation exists then the projective plane *C* is self-dual.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In the special case that the projective plane is of the PG(2, *K*) type, with *K* a division ring, a duality is called a **reciprocity**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] By the fundamental theorem of projective geometry a reciprocity is the composition of an automorphic function of *K* and a homography.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If the automorphism involved is the identity, then the reciprocity is called a **projective correlation**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A correlation of order two (an involution) is called a **polarity**.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] If a correlation *φ* is not a polarity then *φ*2 is a nontrivial collineation.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It can be shown that a projective plane has the same number of lines as it has points (infinite or finite).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The number *N* is called the **order** of the projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The projective plane of order 2 is called the Fano plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] See also the article on finite geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Using the vector space construction with finite fields there exists a projective plane of order *N* = *p**n*, for each prime power *p**n*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In fact, for all known finite projective planes, the order *N* is a prime power.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The existence of finite projective planes of other orders is an open question.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The only general restriction known on the order is the Bruck–Ryser–Chowla theorem that if the order *N* is congruent to 1 or 2 mod 4, it must be the sum of two squares.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The next case *N* = 10 has been ruled out by massive computer calculations.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Nothing more is known; in particular, the question of whether there exists a finite projective plane of order *N* = 12 is still open.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Another longstanding open problem is whether there exist finite projective planes of *prime* order which are not finite field planes (equivalently, whether there exists a non-Desarguesian projective plane of prime order).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] A projective plane of order *N* is a Steiner S(2, *N* + 1, *N*2 + *N* + 1) system (see Steiner system).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Conversely, one can prove that all Steiner systems of this form (*λ* = 2) are projective planes.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The number of mutually orthogonal Latin squares of order *N* is at most *N* − 1.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] *N* − 1 exist if and only if there is a projective plane of order *N*.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Projective planes may be thought of as projective geometries of dimension two.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Higher-dimensional projective geometries can be defined in terms of incidence relations in a manner analogous to the definition of a projective plane.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The smallest projective space of dimension 3 is PG(3,2).
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] These turn out to be "tamer" than the projective planes since the extra degrees of freedom permit Desargues' theorem to be proved geometrically in the higher-dimensional geometry.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] This means that the coordinate "ring" associated to the geometry must be a division ring (skewfield) *K*, and the projective geometry is isomorphic to the one constructed from the vector space *K**d*+1, i.e.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] As in the construction given earlier, the points of the *d*-dimensional projective space PG(*d*, *K*) are the lines through the origin in *K**d*+1 and a line in PG(*d*, *K*) corresponds to a plane through the origin in *K**d*+1.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] In fact, each *i*-dimensional object in PG(*d*, *K*), with *i* < *d*, is an (*i* + 1)-dimensional (algebraic) vector subspace of *K**d*+1 ("goes through the origin").
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] The projective spaces in turn generalize to the Grassmannian spaces.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] It can be shown that if Desargues' theorem holds in a projective space of dimension greater than two, then it must also hold in all planes that are contained in that space.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Since there are projective planes in which Desargues' theorem fails (non-Desarguesian planes), these planes can not be embedded in a higher-dimensional projective space.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Only the planes from the vector space construction PG(2, *K*) can appear in projective spaces of higher dimension.
[src:projective-geometry/projective-plane] Some disciplines in mathematics restrict the meaning of projective plane to only this type of projective plane since otherwise general statements about projective spaces would always have to mention the exceptions when the geometric dimension is two.
